name: Ragnar Trail Wawayanda Lake
intro: Way way up in Wawayanda – announcing our newest East Coast Ragnar Trail Relay; Ragnar Trail Wawayanda Lake presented by Salomon, in association with New York Road Runners. Located about 50 miles outside the lights of New York City is a hidden gem called Wawayanda (pronounced wah - way -  yanda )  State Park. This northern New Jersey venue features a serene lake surrounded by forested hills, and a long stretch of the Appalachian Trail. Teams of 8 (or 4) members will run relay-style over two days and one night, to conquer a set of single-track trails that start and stop at Ragnar Village. Runners will set up camp on the shores of Wawayanda Lake. When the sun goes down, runners will revive and experience the party vibe. Ragnar Trail is like summer camp for adults, with beer, bonfires, s’mores, and a kickass finisher medal. Mark your running calendar for Oct. 6 - 7. and be prepared to find your #innerWILD.

village:
The Ragnar Village is the heart and soul of the event. Each trail begins and ends in Ragnar Village. It is the start line, the finish line, and the exchange point. After each loop you will return to the support of your teammates and the adulation of the teams around you. Ragnar Village will be complete with:

  •  Bonfire
  •  Food & snacks (Friday night dinner included for each runner) 
  • Beer Garden Sales
  •  Movies 
  •  S’mores, Coffee, & Hot Cocoa  
  • Yoga
  • Massage 
  •  Canoe and Paddleboat Rentals                                                               
  •  Music
  •  Billions of stars
     

The Ragnar Village is located at Wawayanda State Park: 885 Warwick Turnpike, Hewitt, NJ 07421

 - There will be no Indoor shower facilites at the event but there will be outdoor showers to rinse off(cold water). BIODEGRADABLE SOAP ONLY TO BE USED.

 - There will be portable toilets as well as an indoor bathhouse with compostable toilets and changing rooms. 

 - Swimming in the lake will not be allowed (closes after Labor Day) but participants will be able to rent canoes and paddleboats during the event

 

Team Campsite

Teams may select their campsite upon arrival (first come, first served). We ask you to try and keep your campsite to 300 square-feet/ 17' x 17'.  Camping is FREE to runners, family, friends, and crew on Thursday and Friday nights. For more information on your team’s campsite please see the Plan Your Trip tab. 

 

Black Bears in Area

 There are black bears in this area. Do not leave food, garbage, smelly items left out at your campsite. If you see a black bear out on the trail make noise, raise your arms and make yourself look big.

Ragnar Trail Wawayanda Lake is just around the corner. Make the weekend even more meaningful by fundraising for a Ragnar charity partner or your favorite charity on everydayhero, the official fundraising platform of Ragnar Relay Series! 

Simply go here (or click on the everydayhero logo above) and choose your favorite charity – it’s that easy!  Your fundraising page will be created and you can start making every step count.

To date, the Ragnar community has fundraised over 1 million dollars so let's keep it going!

Team RWB's mission is to enrich the lives of America's veterans by connecting them to their community through physical and social activity. Please email Donnie Starling (donnie.starling@teamrwb.org) for more information on how to get involved.

 

Back on My Feet is thrilled to be partnering with Ragnar Trail presented by Salomon - Wawayanda Lake for 2016. Back on My Feet combats homelessness through the power of running, community support, and essential employment and housing resources. We believe in the philosophy similar to Ragnar that “there is magic when we come together and accomplish something we could never do alone." At Back on My Feet we see this every Monday, Wednesday and Friday at 5:45am when volunteers from the community come together with individuals experiencing homelessness to run side by side and support each other mile by mile.

If you and 7 of your friends, family, co-workers or strangers seek to together conquer an adventure in camping and running - this race is for you. Your also have the chance to make this race even more meaningful and FundRace for Back on My Feet.

The benefits are great but most importantly you will be making a difference in the lives of individuals experiencing homelessness. With every $1 you raise it returns nearly $2.50 to the local community through increased economic output from employment and reduction in costs for shelter, medical services, incarceration, and drug and alcohol treatment. Back on My Feet proves that there is hope, that individuals can achieve things they never thought possible, and that there are people who will support them along the way.

legs.name: Green Loop - Wingdam Trail
legs.description: The Green loop is the easiest of the three loops but that doesn't make it EASY! Runners will start off by going against runner traffic and back behind the camping area where they will get unto Iron Mtn Trail. You will quickly turn off this trail and run on the side of the main road for about a quarter mile. Be sure to pay attention to the turns or you will find yourself running out of the park! You will turn off the main road onto another paved path under a canopy of trees and alongside a creek that may or may not be running depending on the amount of rain there has been this season. You will then cross paths with the yellow loop at about mile 1.5 and wave hello as you continue onto Laurel Pond Trail. This is a wide trail and fairly flat though you will slowly be gaining elevation as you make your way to Wingdam Trail. In less than a mile you will make a sharp right on Wingdam Trail so pay attention! This trail is single track and VERY TECHNICAL! Please take your time and pick up those feet! At about mile 2.75 you will reconnect with the red and yellow loops and make your way back to the Village!

legs.name: Yellow Loop - Twin Bridges Trail
legs.description: This loop is our intermediate loop and it's a good one! Runners will start out going against runner traffic for about a 1/4 mile where they will then break off from the pack. Please pay attention to signs and volunteer direction so you don't run this loop backwards! You will run past the Historic Furnace and shortly thereafter cross paths with the green loop at about 1/2 a mile and then continue through the camping areas and get unto Double Pond Trail and disappear into the trees. Now the fun begins! You will be on Double Pond for about a 1/4 mile and then turn onto Twin Bridges trail so don't miss the signs! You will stay on Twin Bridges for over a mile where you will then get onto Cherry Ridge Road for a 1/4 mile and then onto Laurel Pond for less than a 1/4 mile and then onto Sitting Bear Trail where you will join up with the Red Loop runners. You will run together for about a mile and a half back to the village on Sitting Bear Trail and then Wingdam Trail. Sitting Bear Trail is VERY TECHNICAL! Lots of rocks and roots so watch your step!

legs.name: Red Loop - Wawayanda
legs.description: We call this one Wawayanda Lake Trail as you are making a loop around the lake. You will be deep in the woods for most of it but will catch glimpses of the lake throughout the run. Runners will start out running through the camping area and getting onto Pumphouse Trail. You will be on this trail for about 2 miles and then will turn onto Cherry Ridge road where you will pass the only water station on the loop so fill up! You will be on Cherry Ridge for less than 1/2 a mile and then turn onto Timber Trail. You will stay on this trail for 1/2 a mile and then get onto South End Trail for another 1/2 mile and then unto Sitting Bear trail where you will meet up with the Yellow loop and run the last mile and a half together back to the Village. This loop is TECHNICAL!!! There are sections that are very very rocky and some sections that are very very rooty and some sections that are both very rocky AND rooty! So please pick up your feet and pay attention! This is a great loop so enjoy!
